<div style="padding:2rem;font-family:monospace;max-width:700px;background:#0d0d0d;min-height:100vh;color:#ccc">
  <a href="/" style="color:#888;font-size:0.85rem">← Back to index</a>
  <h1 style="color:#fff;margin:0.5rem 0 0.25rem">Wildcard Encoding — *param vs :param contrast</h1>
  <p style="color:#888;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
    Star segments skip findHandler's final <code>decodeURIComponent()</code>.
    <code>%2F</code> stays encoded in *param values — contrast with :param.
    Test: <a href="/encoding-wildcard/a/b/c">/encoding-wildcard/a/b/c</a>
    or <a href="/encoding-wildcard/..%2Fadmin" style="color:#4a4">/encoding-wildcard/..%2Fadmin</a>
  </p>

  {{!-- Wildcard value --}}
  <div style="background:#1a1a1a;border:1px solid {{if @model.hasEncodedSlash '#4a4' (if @model.hasDots '#f44' '#555')}};border-radius:6px;padding:1rem;margin-bottom:1rem">
    <div style="color:#888;font-size:0.8rem;margin-bottom:4px">WILDCARD VALUE from params.path</div>
    <code style="color:{{if @model.hasEncodedSlash '#4a4' '#ccc'}};font-size:1.1rem">
      path = "{{@model.rawParam}}"
    </code>
    <div style="font-size:0.8rem;margin-top:8px">
      {{#if @model.hasEncodedSlash}}
        <span style="color:#4a4">SAFE: %2F preserved — star segments skip final decodeURIComponent. If this were a :param, the value would be decoded to contain /</span>
      {{else if @model.hasSlash}}
        <span style="color:#888">Contains literal / from URL path segments — wildcard (.+) captures across / boundaries</span>
      {{else}}
        <span style="color:#888">Normal single-segment value</span>
      {{/if}}
    </div>
  </div>

  {{!-- Browser value --}}
  <div style="background:#1a1a1a;border:1px solid #4a4;border-radius:6px;padding:1rem;margin-bottom:1rem">
    <div style="color:#4a4;font-size:0.8rem;margin-bottom:4px">BROWSER VALUE</div>
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td style="color:#ccc"><code>window.location.pathname</code></td>
          <td><code style="color:#ccc;word-break:break-all">{{this.windowPathname}}</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="color:#ccc"><code>window.location.href</code></td>
          <td><code style="color:#ccc;word-break:break-all;font-size:0.8rem">{{this.windowHref}}</code></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  {{!-- Key contrast --}}
  <div style="background:#111;border:1px solid #f90;border-radius:6px;padding:1rem;margin-bottom:1rem">
    <div style="color:#f90;font-size:0.8rem;margin-bottom:8px">:param vs *param — THE CRITICAL DIFFERENCE</div>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Segment Type</th>
          <th>Regex</th>
          <th>shouldDecodes</th>
          <th>%2F behavior</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td style="color:#f44"><code>:param</code> (dynamic)</td>
          <td><code>([^/]+)</code></td>
          <td style="color:#f44">true</td>
          <td style="color:#f44">Decoded to /</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="color:#4a4"><code>*param</code> (star)</td>
          <td><code>(.+)</code></td>
          <td style="color:#4a4">false</td>
          <td style="color:#4a4">Stays as %2F</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="color:#888;font-size:0.8rem;margin-top:8px">
      Both go through normalizePath() which decodes then re-encodes / and %.
      The difference is findHandler(): dynamic segments get a final decodeURIComponent(),
      star segments don't. This is controlled by the shouldDecodes array in route-recognizer.
    </p>
  </div>

  {{!-- Wildcard CSPT note --}}
  <div style="background:#1a1a1a;border:1px solid #333;border-radius:6px;padding:1rem">
    <div style="color:#888;font-size:0.8rem;margin-bottom:4px">WILDCARD CSPT VECTORS</div>
    <p style="color:#ccc;font-size:0.85rem;line-height:1.6;margin:0">
      Since %2F stays encoded in *param, the primary CSPT vector for wildcards is:
      <br/>1. <strong>Literal /</strong> from URL path segments (captured by <code>(.+)</code>)
      <br/>2. <strong>Hash routing</strong> (<code>locationType: 'hash'</code>) — full path is client-controlled
      <br/>3. <strong>Programmatic navigation</strong> via <code>transitionTo</code> with attacker-controlled values
      <br/>
      <br/>For encoded-slash attacks, target <code>:param</code> routes instead.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
